"script": "When a germ invades your body, your brain does something cruel on purpose: it cranks up your temperature. You see, your immune cells release chemicals that tell your hypothalamus to crank up the heat, which is why you shiver even though you feel like you're burning. And this fever isn't a malfunction, it's a weapon. Most bacteria and viruses thrive at your normal temperature, but a few degrees hotter slows them down and damages them. Meanwhile, your white blood cells move faster and hunt harder in the heat. So that miserable burning feeling is your body cooking the invaders alive to save you.",
